===Etymology 3===
{{zh-forms|alt=蜀}}

Form used as the colloquial reading for “one” in most Min varieties: {{w|Fuzhou}}/Fuding ''suoʔ<sup>8</sup>'', Fuqing ''θyo<sup>8</sup>'', Gutian ''syøʔ<sup>8</sup>'', Ningde ''søʔ<sup>8</sup>'', Zhouning ''sɔʔ<sup>8</sup>'', {{w|Putian}} ''ɬoʔ<sup>8</sup>'', {{w|Xiamen}}/Quanzhou/Yongchun/Zhangzhou ''tsit̚<sup>8</sup>'', Leizhou/{{w|Haikou}} ''ziak<sup>8</sup>'', Longyan ''tse<sup>4</sup>'', Youxi ''ɕie<sup>7</sup>'', Jian'ou/Songxi ''tsi<sup>5</sup>'', Jianyang ''tsi<sup>8</sup>''. Whether all of the forms above are related and their origins remain unelucidated; they may be derived from {{m|zh|sc=Hani|蜀}} (cf. {{m|zh|sc=Hant|獨||single, alone}}; often written when read with the colloquial reading), {{m|zh|sc=Hant|隻}} (< {{m|sit-pro|*kV-tek}}) or {{m|zh|禃}}. Some Fujian dialects use {{m|zh|sc=Hant|個}} and {{m|zh|寡}} for “one”.

